2. Secured and monitored web infrastructure

User types https://www.foobar.com in the browser.
DNS sends the request to the load balancer.
The request goes through a firewall.
HAProxy receives the HTTPS request.
HAProxy uses the SSL certificate to decrypt the traffic.
Then HAProxy sends the request to one of the two servers.
Each server has Nginx, an application server, codebase, MySQL, and a monitoring client.

Infrastructure:

User
  |
DNS: www.foobar.com
  |
Firewall
  |
HAProxy load balancer + SSL certificate + monitoring client
  |
  |----------------|
  v                v
Firewall          Firewall
Server 1          Server 2
Nginx             Nginx
App server        App server
Codebase          Codebase
MySQL Primary     MySQL Replica
Monitoring        Monitoring

Why we added firewalls:
Firewalls protect the servers from unwanted traffic.
They allow only trusted traffic, such as HTTP, HTTPS, or SSH from allowed sources.

Why we added an SSL certificate:
The SSL certificate allows the website to use HTTPS.
HTTPS encrypts the traffic between the user and the website.
This protects sensitive data like passwords and personal information.

Why we added monitoring clients:
Monitoring clients collect information about each server.
They help us know if a server is down, slow, overloaded, or has errors.

What firewalls are for:
Firewalls control incoming and outgoing network traffic.
They block dangerous or unauthorized traffic.

Why traffic is served over HTTPS:
HTTPS keeps communication secure by encrypting data.
It also helps users trust the website.

What monitoring is used for:
Monitoring is used to check server health and performance.
It can track CPU, memory, disk usage, network traffic, errors, and application status.

How the monitoring tool collects data:
A monitoring client is installed on each server.
The client collects logs and metrics.
Then it sends the data to a monitoring service like Sumologic.

How to monitor web server QPS:
QPS means queries per second or requests per second.
To monitor QPS, we can collect Nginx access logs or Nginx metrics.
The monitoring client sends this data to the monitoring service.
Then we create a dashboard or alert to show the number of requests per second.

Issues with this infrastructure:

1. SSL termination at the load balancer:
SSL is terminated at HAProxy.
This means traffic is encrypted between the user and HAProxy, but may not be encrypted between HAProxy and the servers.
This can be a security risk inside the network.

2. Only one MySQL server accepts writes:
Only the Primary database can accept write operations.
If the Primary database fails, the application cannot write new data.
This makes the Primary database a single point of failure for writes.

3. Same components on every server:
Each server has Nginx, application server, codebase, and MySQL.
This can be hard to manage and scale.
If one component needs more resources, we cannot scale it separately.
For example, the database may need more power than the web server.
It is better to separate components into different dedicated servers when the system grows.
